args: A platoon led by Commander Kirsty\nhas been ordered to hold a base located\nin a mountainous border region.
Looks like we're completely surrounded.\nAin't that a kick in the pants?
I hear we're surrounded by Barthe forces.\nIs there any chance it's a different army\nthat's trying to fool us into thinking so?

Not likely, ma'am. Their battle standards
and uniforms are all of Barthe make,
and it's difficult to imagine someone
else going to all that trouble.
In another piece of bad news, they appear\nto have five times our current numbers.
Only Barthe scum would break a truce.\nCurse them and all their kind!
This was just supposed to be a temporary\ngarrison! We're not equipped for a siege!\nW-we're doomed! All of us!
Stow that talk! Back to your posts!\nAnd in the future, if I want your opinion\non a matter, I WILL ASK YOU FOR IT!
A commander cannot tolerate unbridled\nspeculation and panic among her troops.\nThat way lies only anarchy.
Barthe may well be flouting the truce,\nbut we lack the information necessary\nto conclude that with any confidence.
And besides, the state of the truce\nhas no bearing on our current orders.
Defend the base until the last man?
Exactly. Now then, what do you predict\nour enemy's next move to be?
Considering their numbers, they'll likely\nbe satisfied with cutting off our supply\nlines and trying to starve us out.
Though I wouldn't put it past them to poke\nus from time to time just to remind the\nmen how dire their situation is.
Then how would you defend this base\nif that is, indeed, their plan?
I wouldn't. If we try to hold it all,\nthey'll ferret out our weak points\nand pick us apart like crows.
I suggest consolidating our forces in\na specific area and defending that.
Interesting. On another note,\nwhen can we expect reinforcements?

Messengers have been dispatched,
but they'll take some time to arrive.
Looks like we'll have to hunker down
here for the long haul.
On a more positive note, I requested\nextra stocks of rations and fresh water\nfrom HQ before we left.
To be honest, ma'am, I had a bad feeling\nabout this assignment from the start.
It almost makes up for the way you shirked\nyour guard duty after we arrived.
Hey, you're a taskmaster, you know?\nI can't possibly do everything myself.
I don't recall ordering you to do so.
Not this again... Er, what I mean is,\nma'am, maybe you can just let it slide\nconsidering our current situation?
It's in my nature to work alone, \nand sometimes it gets the best of me.

The ＂lone wolf＂ has long been a convenient
excuse for soldiers. That being said,
I know we all have our own strengths
and weaknesses to contend with.
Exactly, ma'am! Always use the right tool\nfor the job, as they say.

However, you should trust that I will
take your ＂nature＂ into account when
considering your next assignment.
Now then...
Attention, all units! We will establish a\ndefensive perimeter at this location!
Reinforcements are en route!\nIf we stand fast and hold the line,\nwe WILL win the day!
Oh, sure. Just hold the line.\nPiece of cake...

Determine how much of this base is
defensible and assign men to those areas.
And if the enemy attacks, make sure they
regret that decision.
Sorry, ma'am, but I thought we'd come\nto an understanding in terms of how\nI preferred solo assignments.

You told me to use the right tool for
the job, yes? And I can think of no
better use for a lone wolf than to
round up all of his packmates.
That is not in ANY way what I meant.
That's a rather long-winded way to say\n＂Right away, Commander.＂
Man, she REALLY needs to relax.\nMaybe take a spa day or something...
Sir, the perimeter has been completed.\nWhat are our next orders?
Oh? In that case, stand down for now.\nI'll take care of things from here.
Don't worry about it. With me on guard,\nnot even a mouse will be able to break\nthrough this perimeter.
In that case, some rest will be welcome.\nMe and the boys are exhausted.
Yeah, yeah. Get outta here already.
Thank hell THAT'S over. This whole\n＂giving orders＂ thing really ain't for me.
Anyway, the perimeter looks solid,\nso now we just whittle and whistle\nuntil the cavalry arrives.
It's gonna be tough with so few troops,\nbut we'll just have to make it work.\nCan't let Kirsty down, after all.
Still, until there's actually an enemy\nwaving a sword in my face, there's no\nharm in kicking my feet up and... Huh?
Enemy forces incoming from the north!\nEveryone to your stations!
Attacking in the middle of the night, eh?\nLooks like this is gonna be rough for\nboth sides.
I tell ya, sometimes a guy just can't\ncatch a break... Er, understood, soldier!\nI'm on my way!
